Introduction

This project comes from a textbook called Data Science in R - A Case Studies Approach to Computational Reasoning and Problem Solving, by Deborah Nolan and Duncan Temple Lang. This particular case study was contributed by Cari Kaufman of UC Berkeley and Duncan Temple Lang of UC Davis. I have a strong interest in leveraging Statistics and Machine Learning to trade algorithmically, so this case study appealed to me greatly. I try not to copy everything directly, so for some of the functions I implement my own code to complete the same task.

Pairs trading is essentially a way to leverage two positively cointegrated securities to make money. Developed in the 1980s at Morgan Stanley, the idea is that two positively cointegrated securities will have a (relatively) steady ratio between their share prices. If you look at the ratio of the share prices of secutiry 1 to security 2, and they tend to fluctuate around a certain point, this shows that the pair is well suited for pairs trading. One can establish a historical average for the ratio between the two securities. Its when the ratio moves away from the historical average that the opportunity to make money comes about. Quoting the textbook example: if stock 1 is doing better than it typically does, relative to stock 2, then we should sell stock 1 and buy stock 2. This is called opening a position. Then, when the ratio returns to its historical average, we should buy stock 1 and sell stock 2. This is called closing the position.

Its easier to see visually.

#read in the data
sp500 <- read.csv("^GSPC.csv")
dow <- read.csv("^DJI.csv")

#put the S&P and Dow into one data frame- only interested in adjusted closing prices
dow <- dow %>% select(Date, Adj.Close)
sp500 <- sp500 %>% select(Date, Adj.Close)
sp_dj <- full_join(dow, sp500, by = 'Date')
names(sp_dj) <- c("Date", "Adj.Close_Dow", "Adj.Close_SP500")
#create the ratio
sp_dj$Ratio <- sp_dj$Adj.Close_Dow/sp_dj$Adj.Close_SP500
#format the date column
sp_dj$Date <- ymd(sp_dj$Date)

#make the graph function that accepts ratio, # of std devs, and line colors
plotRatio <- function(df, k = 1, col_mean = "red", col_sd = "darkgreen", db = "1 year", ...){
  ggplot(data = df, aes(x = Date, y = Ratio)) + 
    geom_line() + 
    scale_x_date(date_labels = "%Y", date_breaks = db) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = mean(df$Ratio), color = col_mean) + 
    geom_hline(yintercept = (mean(df$Ratio) + k * sd(df$Ratio)), color = col_sd, linetype = "dashed") +
    geom_hline(yintercept = (mean(df$Ratio) - k * sd(df$Ratio)), color = col_sd, linetype = "dashed")
}
plotRatio(sp_dj)

Here we visualize the ratio between the share prices of the S&P 500 and the Dow Jones Index from 1990 to 1995. We can see that the ratio fluctuates around a mean of 7.95 (represented by the red line), and the standard deviation from that mean is 0.21 (represented by the dark green dashed lines). One would open a position when the ratio is above/below one of the green lines, and close the position when the ratio returns to the mean.

Finding Pairs Suitable for Pairs Trading

One thing the book doesnt go over until the end is if a pair of securities are even suitable for pairs trading. I thought that should be the first thing I do. I found through research that the base requirement is not correlation, but cointegration. For example, two stocks could both have an up day and be positively correlated, but the degree of correlation can vary greatly. There also could be no underlying reason as to why both stocks went up that is intuitive and explainable. However, I learned that if the two stocks are cointegrated, this means much more. Cointegration means that two stocks can fluctuate on a random walk, but the distance between them is bounded. The analogy I found in an article went like this: A man was drinking in a pub and decided to leave, and he took his dog with him. They started walking home and came to an intersection, so the man put the dog on the leash. The drunk man was walking randomly, and so was the dog- but the distance between them at any given time was bounded by the leash. The man and dog were cointegrated.

Future Development

I found an article in a tweet from Quantopian about how to use t-SNE and DBSCAN to identify pairs suitable for pairs trading here. Ive already successfully used this workflow in an internship to summarize Mutual Funds, so Im very interested in exploring this more.

Once I understood the idea behind cointegration, I looked online to see how to test if two time series were cointegrated, and I came to this blog post that had the following function. It takes two identical time series and outputs a p-value (< 0.05 means highly cointegrated).

library(tseries)
## Warning: package 'tseries' was built under R version 3.4.1
cointegration<-function(x,y)
{
  vals<-data.frame(x,y)
  beta<-coef(lm(vals[,2]~vals[,1]+0,data=vals))[1]
  (adf.test(vals[,2]-beta*vals[,1], alternative="stationary", k=0))$p.value
}

Now I can test if any two stocks are suitable for pairs trading. For the sake of confirmation, lets test the S&P 500 and the Dow Jones:

cointegration(sp500$Adj.Close, dow$Adj.Close)
## [1] 0.8289649

Uh oh. Based on the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test, these two stocks over the 90-95 time period arent really suitable for pairs trading. This makes sense, because though this is the time the textbook uses for example, they do have to close a position at a loss because the 5 years is up.

Finding Opening and Closing Positions

To visualize even more what we are doing here, we can highlight the positions on a ratio graph where we will open and close positions. Well start by writing a function to compute the next position given a starting position or day to start from. According to the text, this will allow us to use the function to find all of the positions.

This function will accept the ratio vector, the start day that will act as an index for the ratio vector, and a value for k. We can also add in the mean of the ratio and the standard deviation of the ratio.

findNextPos <- function(ratio, startDay = 1, k = 1,
                        m = mean(ratio), s = sd(ratio)){
  #define the upper and lower bounds
  up <- m + k*s
  down <- m - k*s
  
  #if the start day isn't 1, you've got to prune your ratio vector accordingly
  if(startDay > 1)
    ratio <- ratio[-(1:(startDay-1))]
  
  
  #define a flag that turns true if the ratio goes above or below the bounds
  isExtreme <- ratio >= up | ratio <= down
  
  #if the ratio never crosses the bounds, return an integer
  if(!any(isExtreme))
    return(integer())
  
  #define 'start' as either above or below the ratio
  start <- which(isExtreme)[1]
  #define when it's back down to the mean
  backToNormal <- if(ratio[start] > up)
    ratio[-(1:start)] <= m
  else
    ratio[-(1:start)] >= m
  #return either the end of the position or the index of the end of the vector
  #it could return NA for not ended, i.e. #which(backToNormal)[1]
  #for both cases. But then the caller has to interpret that.
  
  end <- if(any(backToNormal))
    which(backToNormal)[1] + start
  else
    length(ratio)
  
  c(start, end) + startDay - 1
}

Since we can find one position, we can use an iterative process in order to find all of the positions.

#pass all the previous things
getPositions <- function(ratio, k = 1, m = mean(ratio), s = sd(ratio)){
  #initialize list and "current" date counter
  when = list()
  cur = 1
  
  #while the date is less than the number of entities in ratio, 
  #find the next position. If findNextPos returns a vector of length 0, 
  #we never open a position- this pair of stocks is not suitable for pairs trading. 
  #If the closing position is the last date, the pair never reverted to the mean
  while(cur < length(ratio)){
    tmp <- findNextPos(ratio, cur, k, m, s)
    if(length(tmp) == 0)
      break
    when[[length(when) + 1]] = tmp
    if(is.na(tmp[2]) || tmp[2] == length(ratio))
      break
    cur = tmp[2]
  }
  return(when)
}

showPositions <- function(df, positions, k = 1, col_mean = "red", col_sd = "darkgreen", db = "1 year", ...){
  open <- vector(mode = "numeric", length = length(positions))
  close <- vector(mode = "numeric", length = length(positions))
  for(i in 1:length(positions)){
    open[i] <- positions[[i]][1]
    close[i] <- positions[[i]][2]
  }
  p <- ggplot(data = df, aes(x = Date, y = Ratio)) + 
    geom_line() + 
    scale_x_date(date_labels = "%Y", date_breaks = db) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = mean(df$Ratio), color = col_mean) + 
    geom_hline(yintercept = (mean(df$Ratio) + k * sd(df$Ratio)), color = col_sd, linetype = "dashed") +
    geom_hline(yintercept = (mean(df$Ratio) - k * sd(df$Ratio)), color = col_sd, linetype = "dashed")
  
  openers <- data.frame(matrix(nrow = length(positions), ncol = 2))
  closers <- data.frame(matrix(nrow = length(positions), ncol = 2))
  
  openers$Date <- df$Date[open]
  openers$Ratio <- df$Ratio[open]
  
  closers$Date <- df$Date[close]
  closers$Ratio <- df$Ratio[close]
  
  o <- geom_point(data = openers, aes(x = Date, y = Ratio), size = 5, color = "darkgreen", shape = 1)
  c <- geom_point(data = closers, aes(x = Date, y = Ratio), size = 5, color = "red", shape = 1)
  p + o + c
}


showPositions(att_vzw, positions, db = "5 years")

The green circles are where we would open positions, and the red circles are where we would close. We take advantage of the fact that the ratio is mean-reverting to make money. Now we can work on calculating how much we would actually make!

Computing the Profit for a Position

We want to write a function to compute the profit for each position. It will be called positionProfit(), and it will take the position vector and the stock prices. The code will be commented to explain how it works.

#pass the position list of vectors, stock prices, and the percentage we pay in commission of the total dollar amount
positionProfit <- function(pos, stockPriceA, stockPriceB, ratioMean = mean(stockPriceA/stockPriceB), p = 0.001, byStock = FALSE){
  
  #validate the pos object is a list of vectors, and if we want the profit by stock, create the df
  if(is.list(pos)){
    ans <- sapply(pos, positionProfit, stockPriceA, stockPriceB, ratioMean, p, byStock)
    if(byStock)
      rownames(ans) = c("A", "B", "commission")
    return(ans)
  }
  
  #get the stock prices at the start and end of each position
  priceA <- stockPriceA[pos]
  priceB <- stockPriceB[pos]
  
  #how many units can we buy of A and B with $1? (Generally a small fraction)
  unitsOfA <- 1/priceA[1]
  unitsOfB <- 1/priceB[1]
  
  #get the dollar amount of how many units we would buy of A and B
  #at the cost at the end of the position of each
  amt <- c(unitsOfA * priceA[2], unitsOfB * priceB[2])
  
  #figure out which stock we are selling
  sellWhat <- if(priceA[1]/priceB[1] > ratioMean) 
    "A" 
  else 
    "B"
  
  #compute the profit based on which stock it was
  profit <- if(sellWhat == "A")
    c((1 - amt[1]), (amt[2] - 1), - p * sum(amt))
            else
              c((1 - amt[2]), (amt[1] - 1), -p * sum(amt))
  
  #if we want a more detailed look of the profit by position, set byStock = TRUE
  if(byStock)
    profit
  else
    sum(profit)
    
}

Now we want to test that this is working. We can test it on the first position for the DJI and GSPC.

positionProfit(c(1,2), c(3838.48, 8712.87), c(459.11, 1100.65), p = 0)
## [1] 0.1274807

Based on the text, this is exactly what we want to see. And if we round this to two decimals, we see that on that position we made $0.13. Now we can see the profits for each position in our AT&T vs Verizon example

Finding the Optimal Value of K

We now can use the functions we created to find the best value of k from training data and apply it to test data. We will split the data into training and testing sets.

#create the training and testing sets
i = 1:floor(nrow(att_vzw)/2)
train = att_vzw[i, ]
test = att_vzw[-i, ]
rtrain = train$Ratio
rtest = test$Ratio

#set the max value of k to look between
kmax <- max(rtrain)
#set the min value of k to look between
kmin <- min(rtrain)
#compute the sequence of calues for k that we want to explore
ks <- seq(kmin, kmax, length = 1000)
#compute the mean of the ratio just to have for later
m <- mean(att_vzw$Ratio)

Now we can loop over the different values of k and compute the profit for that strategy/rule defined by k:

profits <- sapply(ks, 
                  function(k){
                    pos <- getPositions(rtrain, k)
                    sum(positionProfit(pos, train$Adj.Close_att, train$Adj.Close_vzw,
                                       ratioMean = mean(rtrain)))
                  })

plot(ks, profits, type = "l", xlab = "Value of k", ylab = "Profit")

Here we can visualize the distribution of profit for various values of k. It seems we max out our profit around 0.85 or so. Lets see what it actually is

ks[profits == max(profits)]
## [1] 0.8565283 0.8571636 0.8577990

These are the values for k which maximize our profits! Ideally we want one value but these signify the flat region up at the top of our distribution.
